Feature Engineering¶

Target variable¶

In [6]:
# Create new dataset for modeling purpose
data_scm_model = pd.DataFrame()
In [7]:
# By "Detecting Fraud", we mean to properly classify these 2.3% suspected fraud.
# Need to think about performance measure. Since its a imbalance problem, accuracy or even ROC curve might not reflect actual performance
data_scm_model['y_fraud'] = np.where(dataco_scm['Order Status']=='SUSPECTED_FRAUD', 1, 0)
In [8]:
data_scm_model.groupby('y_fraud').size().plot(kind='pie', explode=[0, 0.2], autopct='%1.1f%%', 
                                               colors = ['#5a5a5a','red'])

Section 2: Modeling¶

In [15]:
# Split the data
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(
    data_scm_model.drop(columns=['y_fraud']), data_scm_model['y_fraud'], test_size=0.2, random_state=42)

Logistic Regression¶

In [16]:
# Import library
import tensorflow as tf
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix, plot_roc_curve
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
In [17]:
# Modeling
model_logistic = LogisticRegression()
model_logistic.fit(X_train, y_train)
Out[17]:
LogisticRegression()
In [18]:
# Performance
print('LR Accuracy Score')
display(model_logistic.score(X_test, y_test))

print("Confusion matrix")
display(confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred))
